--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A vector is an arrow with length (magnitude) and direction.
In math, we usually think of vectors as coordinates (e.g., [3, 2] means go 3 units right and 2 units up).
You can scale a vector (multiply by a number) → makes it longer or shorter.
You can add vectors (tip-to-tail method) → gets a new vector.
Vectors are the building blocks of everything in linear algebra.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Linear Combination = Multiply vectors by numbers (scalars) and add them.
Span = All possible points you can reach by making linear combinations of some vectors.
Example: Two vectors in 2D space usually span the entire plane.
Basis Vectors = The simplest set of vectors that can span the whole space (usually î and ĵ — the unit vectors along x and y axes).
If vectors are linearly dependent (one is a multiple of another), their span is smaller (just a line).
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A Linear Transformation is a function that moves every vector in a special way:
Straight lines stay straight.
Grid remains evenly spaced (parallel lines stay parallel).
Origin stays fixed.

Examples: Rotation, scaling, shearing, reflection.
Matrix = A compact way to represent a linear transformation.
The columns of the matrix tell you where the basis vectors (î and ĵ) land after transformation.

Multiplying a matrix by a vector = Apply the transformation to that vector.
